T1  - Learning from Land: Lerma's Guided by the Mountains
AN  - 2157627045
AB  - Let's now enter our home in order to gauge and access what is needed for a good day … a good life.2 Almost twenty years have passed since Vine Deloria and David Wilkins proposed that "(r)acial and ethnic studies can immediately link with political theory because that specialty represents the initial conceptual framework within which the respective minority groups had to be accommodated historically.

The second aspect of the text builds naturally on this foundation: it briefly brackets ontological questions to more explicitly answer political and policy questions, both retrospectively (how to understand the trauma of contact, conflict and attempts at colonialism?), and projectively (how and when might we reestablish Navajo traditions to inform common law and reform institutions?).

Here, Lerma marshals a robust arsenal of concepts drawn from the social sciences, and comparative politics more specifically: the language of state-sponsored settlers, extractive industries, local elites and path dependencies will sound familiar to scholars who have studied colonialism and the "natural resources curse" in all its forms.

Scholars familiar with language drawn from the positive social sciences and policy studies may be surprised to see such models removed from their original context (for PEM, one assumes evolutionary biology and heterodox economics), and then inserted into analyses of extraction and exploitation within the US.
