T1  - Building a Culture of Peace and Collective Memory in Post‐conflict Bosnia and Herzegovina: Sarajevo's Museum of War Childhood
AN  - 2057474071
AB  - The Museum of War Childhood in Sarajevo opened its doors to the public in January 2017. I visited the Museum in the summer of 2017, during a month-long research trip to Bosnia where I was conducting interviews with women survivors of wartime sexual violence. The purpose of my stay was to collect materials on children and war, with a particular interest in children born as a result of war, that is, those whose mothers were raped by members of militias from opposing ethnic groups. During the course of my fieldwork I learned about the Museum serendipitously, while researching the profiles of local non-governmental organizations (NGOs) which provide support to war survivors. Located on a historic street in Sarajevo's Stari Grad (Old Town), the Museum would be an otherwise unassuming presence were it not for the stark black-and-white sign with its name and logo that marks its location. I had no expectations for the visit, as I had not read anything about the Museum or its permanent collection prior to my arrival in Sarajevo. Although I have been actively researching the recent war in the former Yugoslavia for almost a decade, I found myself largely unprepared for the full emotional impact of the Museum's artefacts and video testimonies by those who lived through the war as children. The unmistakeable 'thisness' of the objects and narratives, and the luminous simplicity captured in a child's perspective upon witnessing a harrowing reality, constituting in my own private response what Jan Assman in his work on collective memory calls 'the concretion of identity' as I experienced their 'capacity to reconstruct' the past in the context of a contemporary situation (Assman 1995: 130).
